<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="110" type="range">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="110">Range.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="110">CANADA: Alberta, British Columbia, Manitoba (sw), Northwest Territories (sw), Ontario (Manitoulin Island), Quebec (Gaspe Peninsula), Saskatchewan, Yukon (s). UNITED STATES: Alaska (se interior border), Arizona (n), California, Colorado, Idaho, Montana, North Dakota, Nevada, New Mexico (n), Oregon, South Dakota (w), Utah, Washington, Wyoming, with outlying populations in Nebraska (w), Oklahoma (panhandle), Michigan (Isle Royal) and sporadic in Illinois and Maine, Massachusetts.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="110">
The geographic range of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. secunda" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="secunda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">P. secunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in North America north of Mexico is mapped in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution of Poa secunda subspecies in North America: subsp. secunda (yellow); subsp. juncifolia (blue)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.110.27750.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/240277" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">2</figureCitation>
. Subspecies 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" subspecies="secunda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">secunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs throughout the species range and also reaches into Baja California Norte, Mexico (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution of Poa secunda subspecies in North America: subsp. secunda (yellow); subsp. juncifolia (blue)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.110.27750.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/240277" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">2A</figureCitation>
). The range of subspecies 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" subspecies="juncifolia">juncifolia</taxonomicName>
is almost completely within that of subsp. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" subspecies="secunda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">secunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except for several scattered localities in Arizona, New Mexico and Nebraska; it is absent from Mexico and mostly absent from the Pacific Coast and coastal mountains (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution of Poa secunda subspecies in North America: subsp. secunda (yellow); subsp. juncifolia (blue)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.110.27750.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/240277" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">2B</figureCitation>
). The ranges of varieties are broadly overlapping within their subspecies. Both subspecies have disjunct populations in the Patagonian Andes of Argentina and Chile.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
